One of my major epiphanies in working on the
book and on the article in Fortune Magazine

00:01:32.590 --> 00:01:37.079
before it is just how differently Apple does
business from the way everybody else does

00:01:37.079 --> 00:01:38.130
business.

00:01:38.130 --> 00:01:43.240
And indeed how the Apple way of doing business
is different from what's taught in business

00:01:43.240 --> 00:01:45.009
school.

00:01:45.009 --> 00:01:49.060
And Steve Jobs was quite clear on this, he
didn't particularly care for business school

00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:53.520
and he didn't particularly care for MBA's
in general.

00:01:53.520 --> 00:02:00.479
And part of the reason for doing Apple University
over the past four years was to as he put

00:02:00.479 --> 00:02:04.109
it, "To try to create our own kind of MBA."

00:02:04.109 --> 00:02:11.879
And so I'll ask you to keep in mind as I make
my points how much Apple differs from everybody

00:02:11.879 --> 00:02:12.879
else.

00:02:12.879 --> 00:02:18.849
The question arises, well if they're so exceptional
and they're so unique and they had this extraordinary

00:02:18.849 --> 00:02:22.700
one of a kind leader how much can we learn
from them?

00:02:22.700 --> 00:02:27.980
And I would suggest there absolutely is a
don't try this at home aspect to Apple's way

00:02:27.980 --> 00:02:29.060
of doing business.

00:02:29.060 --> 00:02:35.170
Having said that Apple is currently the world's
most valuable company and is absolutely crushing

00:02:35.170 --> 00:02:41.959
it in a way and growing in a way that no large
company does, and maybe no large company ever

00:02:41.959 --> 00:02:47.120
has and so I would submit that if they do
things differently it's at least worth asking

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:51.489
the question how and why.

00:02:51.489 --> 00:02:54.049
And I really wish we had one of those set
ups where we could pan the room because I

00:02:54.049 --> 00:02:57.030
just love people sitting on the floor for
a talk –

00:02:57.030 --> 00:02:58.530
[laughter]

00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:00.040
wonderful.

00:03:00.040 --> 00:03:05.870
A moment on what Apple was like in 1997 when
Steve Jobs returned to the company.

00:03:05.870 --> 00:03:11.870
He would be quoted frequently and in ensuing
years talking about the fact that Apple was

00:03:11.870 --> 00:03:16.829
90 days from insolvency when he rejoined the
company in 1997.

00:03:16.829 --> 00:03:21.920
The company was a shambles; it had too many
factories in the United States and abroad,

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:27.790
it had too much inventory, it had too many
middle managers, Jobs went on to fire about

00:03:27.790 --> 00:03:29.939
4,000 of them.

00:03:29.939 --> 00:03:35.370
The culture in his opinion had become infected
with people who were more interested in making

00:03:35.370 --> 00:03:41.140
money than they were in making beautiful products,
and the company was structurally dysfunctional

00:03:41.140 --> 00:03:43.090
in a way that he would change.

00:03:43.090 --> 00:03:49.060
And the example that I share in the book is
that at the time Apple had 16 advertising

00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:50.060
budgets.

00:03:50.060 --> 00:03:54.670
Now the adverting budgets is a good metaphor
for fiefdoms; if you were a general manager

00:03:54.670 --> 00:03:58.930
in the business and you had an advertising
budget that probably wasn't the only budget

00:03:58.930 --> 00:04:02.939
that you had, you were an important person
in your own right.

00:04:02.939 --> 00:04:07.340
Jobs wanted to eliminate that, he wanted to
get rid of fiefdoms, he got rid of the whole

00:04:07.340 --> 00:04:14.870
notion of general manager, and he wanted to
emphasize the notion of one company, one brand,

00:04:14.870 --> 00:04:17.680
one Apple, and so on.

00:04:17.680 --> 00:04:24.580
And in eliminating the advertising budgets
he was able to say to people who were responsible

00:04:24.580 --> 00:04:29.870
for a product, "If you think your product
deserves advertising spend then you'll come

00:04:29.870 --> 00:04:34.090
to me and ask for advertizing spend and I'll
decide whether or not to give it to you and

00:04:34.090 --> 00:04:40.090
we'll make a decision at a central, at a corporate
level about how to advertise."

00:04:40.090 --> 00:04:41.949
And we all know how that's gone for Apple.

00:04:41.949 --> 00:04:46.970
This was not about cost cutting by the way;
within short order advertising spending at

00:04:46.970 --> 00:04:54.470
Apple increased it didn't decrease and Apple
developed this very virtuous circle of tending

00:04:54.470 --> 00:04:59.570
to only advertise one or two major things
at a time, but there being a halo effect to

00:04:59.570 --> 00:05:05.460
the other products that weren't being advertised
and this worked particularly well once the

00:05:05.460 --> 00:05:10.330
stores were up and running and became a force
of their own.

00:05:10.330 --> 00:05:16.940
Advertise an iPod and people might come in
and buy an iPhone; advertize the iPhone and

00:05:16.940 --> 00:05:22.250
people have to walk past the Macintosh's to
get to the iMac's or the laptops to get to

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:24.440
the iPhone and so on.

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:29.629
And so that's something that Jobs cleaned
up in his first few years back at the company

00:05:29.629 --> 00:05:32.629
in '97.

00:05:32.629 --> 00:05:39.139
Leadership is an important topic when thinking
about Apple, it's also an example of Apple's

00:05:39.139 --> 00:05:40.810
exceptionalism.

00:05:40.810 --> 00:05:45.500
This is Narcissus the Greek god who was in
love with his own image; here he is gazing

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:49.509
into the pond to see his own beautiful self.

00:05:49.509 --> 00:05:57.300
And I just wanted to share the work of a psychotherapist
and business coach named Michael Maccoby who

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:04.199
wrote a Harvest Business School article and
then a book called Narcissistic Leaders.

00:06:04.199 --> 00:06:11.849
And as I was reading this article it goes
on explaining what a narcissist is first of

00:06:11.849 --> 00:06:17.389
all, a narcissist is someone who is visionary,
who is charismatic, who has a willingness

00:06:17.389 --> 00:06:24.520
to bet the company on his or her vision, who
expects to be followed but doesn't necessarily

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:26.479
care if they're loved.

00:06:26.479 --> 00:06:32.080
And as I was readin' this I was thinking,
"My God this person is describing Steve Jobs

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:33.409
without using his name."

00:06:33.409 --> 00:06:37.419
And then in fact Jobs did appear as an example
in Maccoby's work.

00:06:37.419 --> 00:06:42.770
The productive narcissist, and I mentioned
that Maccoby was a business coach and a trained

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:48.069
psychotherapist, the productive narcissist
is someone who can channel their narcissism

00:06:48.069 --> 00:06:53.170
in a productive way and he worked with clients
to help them be not less narcissistic but

00:06:53.170 --> 00:06:55.590
more productively narcissistic.

00:06:55.590 --> 00:07:02.360
And I think that if you dig into this topic
you see that a lot of what makes Apple tick

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:07.539
is because it has been led by this kind of
personality.

00:07:07.539 --> 00:07:11.659
What then you ask happens after the productive
narcissist is gone?

00:07:11.659 --> 00:07:17.560
Well there's two other categories that Maccoby
identifies as business people and he uses

00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:21.099
classical Jungian psychological terms for
this.

00:07:21.099 --> 00:07:25.819
The second category is an obsessive and he
talked about productive obsessives, these

00:07:25.819 --> 00:07:31.060
are people who make the trains run on time,
they're typically a side kick to the productive

00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:37.060
narcissist, they can help the visionary realize
their vision by executing it.

00:07:37.060 --> 00:07:43.949
Tim Cook is a classic, the current CEO of
Apple, is a classic productive obsessive and

00:07:43.949 --> 00:07:49.860
he's been in that role at Apple as Jobs' sidekick
for 10 years and now we'll see how the productive

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:52.300
obsessive can do as the CEO.

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:57.919
There are obsessive's as CEO's of other companies,
but Apple is very much characterized by this

00:07:57.919 --> 00:08:00.539
narcissistic led organization.

00:08:00.539 --> 00:08:04.050
There's a third category, by the way, that
will be of interest to people in the room

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:09.639
because I noticed that the CEO isn't in the
room and that is, unless I'm mistaken then

00:08:09.639 --> 00:08:11.979
I apologize Larry.

00:08:11.979 --> 00:08:13.550
[laughter]

00:08:13.550 --> 00:08:18.530
His third category it's called erotics, an
erotic is someone who in the Jungian sense

00:08:18.530 --> 00:08:24.909
is someone who does feel a need to be loved,
who does not necessarily like to be criticized

00:08:24.909 --> 00:08:26.360
and wants approval.

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:31.639
This is an excellent person to have on a team,
not necessarily the person that you want running

00:08:31.639 --> 00:08:33.770
the company.

00:08:33.770 --> 00:08:35.360
[laughter]

00:08:35.360 --> 00:08:41.230
One of the essential teachings of the modern
business era is that business leaders should

00:08:41.230 --> 00:08:46.510
empower their people, they should push decisions
down into the organization, they should give

00:08:46.510 --> 00:08:52.050
people the rope to hang themselves and to
execute the strategy of the company.

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:54.540
This is not how Apple does things.

00:08:54.540 --> 00:08:59.360
Steve Jobs was a classic micromanager and
the people beneath him micromanaged the people

00:08:59.360 --> 00:09:00.850
beneath them.

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:04.750
No detail is beneath their attention.

00:09:04.750 --> 00:09:09.320
I know I mentioned that he was a narcissist
but he also had obsessive characteristics

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:10.320
as well.

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:14.940
And I discussed this with Maccoby by the way,
I asked Maccoby what he was and he said, "Well

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:21.050
I'm mostly an obsessive but I've got some
narcissistic tendencies to me as well."

00:09:21.050 --> 00:09:26.000
And my example of it I discuss in the book
is an exchange that Jobs had with the marketing

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:31.410
executive whose job it was to send out an
email concurrent with a keynote launch of

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:33.100
a product.

00:09:33.100 --> 00:09:39.410
And this person would email Jobs days before
the keynote to say, "Here's the email that

00:09:39.410 --> 00:09:40.980
will go out."

00:09:40.980 --> 00:09:46.610
And Jobs would object to the grammar in the
email getting down to the placement of a comma

00:09:46.610 --> 00:09:52.710
or a semicolon and they would go back repeatedly
17 times until they got it right.

00:09:52.710 --> 00:09:59.550
To me this is bizarre behavior but not inconsistent
with the micromanagement that Apple embraces.

00:09:59.550 --> 00:10:05.680
I believe, by the way, from my conversations
that Jobs' opinion on the placement of the

00:10:05.680 --> 00:10:06.680
comma was wrong --

00:10:06.680 --> 00:10:08.150
[laughter]

00:10:08.150 --> 00:10:11.060
but that doesn't matter and I think that's
obvious.

00:10:11.060 --> 00:10:15.700
He obviously was very interested in language
but not a grammarian as we know from the Think

00:10:15.700 --> 00:10:18.600
Different campaign.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:20.880
[laughter]

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:27.220
A major part of my book and my research on
Apple is analyzing its secrecy.

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:32.750
I've been able to turn the what was a disadvantage
for me in writing a book about a company that

00:10:32.750 --> 00:10:37.770
it's very secretive into a thesis point about
the company.

00:10:37.770 --> 00:10:44.100
And my line is that every company keeps secrets
but at Apple everything is a secret and Apple

00:10:44.100 --> 00:10:46.570
is particularly good at keeping secrets.

00:10:46.570 --> 00:10:47.570
[laughter]

00:10:47.570 --> 00:10:53.450
They have a hint of a sense of humor about
secrecy; this is an actual T-shirt that you

00:10:53.450 --> 00:10:57.540
can buy at the company store in Cupertino
which is open to the public, "I visited the

00:10:57.540 --> 00:10:58.840
Apple campus.

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:01.720
But that's all I'm allowed to say."

00:11:01.720 --> 00:11:03.250
[laughter]

00:11:03.250 --> 00:11:07.340
I will say it's the one example of a sense
of humor that I've been able to find at Apple

00:11:07.340 --> 00:11:08.340
--

00:11:08.340 --> 00:11:09.340
[laughter]

00:11:09.340 --> 00:11:13.450
but I'm appreciative of it, very appreciative.

00:11:13.450 --> 00:11:19.980
There is a sense of a culture of fear at Apple,
I've heard this from many, many employees

00:11:19.980 --> 00:11:25.240
and I'll say in anticipation of a question
that I typically get is: who are my sources

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:26.240
for the book?

00:11:26.240 --> 00:11:30.500
My sources are people typically who worked
at Apple at all levels of the organization,

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:35.950
very senior, very junior, and in between,
and compared with Walter Isaacson's biography

00:11:35.950 --> 00:11:40.860
of Steve Jobs which is very much a view from
the top, I think that the perspective of a

00:11:40.860 --> 00:11:47.490
junior person, for example, is very valid
in understanding how a company actually operates.

00:11:47.490 --> 00:11:54.140
And secrecy is so important at Apple that
people are afraid to deviate from the secrecy.

00:11:54.140 --> 00:12:00.310
And the hallmark of this is new employee orientation
which is every Monday at Apple, except as

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:05.060
I was told with a straight face when Monday
comes on a holiday.

00:12:05.060 --> 00:12:09.450
That the security briefing is part of new
employee orientation and new employees are

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:16.330
told in a very matter of fact way, "Secrecy
is important here, it's worth money and measured

00:12:16.330 --> 00:12:20.600
in the hundreds of millions of dollars from
the benefit that we get when a product is

00:12:20.600 --> 00:12:26.560
launched and retribution will be severe is
you breach the rules of secrecy.

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:29.430
Termination obviously, maybe you'll be sued
as well."

00:12:29.430 --> 00:12:32.180
And this is on your first day of work at Apple.

00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:33.630
[laughter]

00:12:33.630 --> 00:12:35.520
So why keep secrets?

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:39.680
The first one is good basic business in my
opinion.

00:12:39.680 --> 00:12:42.920
You don't want your competitors knowing what
you're doing, you also don't want customers

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:45.820
knowing what you're doing until you're good
and ready to tell them.

00:12:45.820 --> 00:12:51.500
Now this is a debatable topic in the Internet
world and in the Web world and we can discuss

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:55.940
it with as much time as we have, but Apple's
very clear on the subject.

00:12:55.940 --> 00:13:01.770
Customers, the world, but customers in particular,
should learn about products the day that they're

00:13:01.770 --> 00:13:06.430
released by us and not a moment before then.

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:11.900
And there's good Silicon Valley precedent
on this; other companies have fallen afoul

00:13:11.900 --> 00:13:18.610
of the basic rule of if you've got products
on the shelf in retailer's stores and even

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:23.990
more seriously if you've got product in warehouses,
the last thing you want is customers believing

00:13:23.990 --> 00:13:28.870
that a new version is coming soon because
who's gonna buy a product that's sitting on

00:13:28.870 --> 00:13:31.790
shelves when a new version is coming soon?

00:13:31.790 --> 00:13:36.450
And even Apple hasn't been perfect about this;
quarter before last they acknowledged that

00:13:36.450 --> 00:13:41.820
iPhone 4 sales were hurt because the public
expected an iPhone 5.

00:13:41.820 --> 00:13:46.550
They didn't get it, they were very disappointed
about this, they got the iPhone 4S instead

00:13:46.550 --> 00:13:51.480
and it hurt Apple so badly that they went
on to sell 37 million iPhones in the last

00:13:51.480 --> 00:13:54.370
quarter and rang up a $13 billion profit.

00:13:54.370 --> 00:14:00.610
But the quarter before that they did acknowledge
that the rumor mill had had a negative impact.

00:14:00.610 --> 00:14:06.790
But that's among the reasons anyway for keeping
secrets to outsiders.

00:14:06.790 --> 00:14:13.220
But what I've realized in studying the company
is that Apple takes internal secrecy as seriously

00:14:13.220 --> 00:14:15.540
as it does external secrecy.

00:14:15.540 --> 00:14:21.370
And I've likened Apple employees to a horse
fitted with blinders; you don't look left,

00:14:21.370 --> 00:14:27.360
you don't look right, you charge forward at
Apple and you don't multi-task by the way.

00:14:27.360 --> 00:14:32.600
It has been humbling for me when I came to
realize how focused Apple people are because

00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:41.480
I'm a multi-tasker, I'm constantly doing many
things, and at Apple below a certain level

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:49.290
and that level is high you don't do many things,
you tend to do one thing.

00:14:49.290 --> 00:14:53.940
I don't know if it's an unintended consequence
but a realization that I had on this topic

00:14:53.940 --> 00:14:59.640
of internal secrecy is that I've been told
over and over and I've come to believe that

00:14:59.640 --> 00:15:04.870
below a certain level again there's very little
politicking at Apple.

00:15:04.870 --> 00:15:09.750
And that makes sense because how can you play
politics when you don't have the information

00:15:09.750 --> 00:15:12.140
with which to play politics?

00:15:12.140 --> 00:15:16.160
It is none of your business what I'm doing
[chuckles] and it's none of my business what

00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:19.290
you're doing so what do we have to talk about?

00:15:19.290 --> 00:15:25.080
And I skipped over an example on the outside
world; it's my belief from my 15 years in

00:15:25.080 --> 00:15:29.280
Silicon Valley that engineers in particular
love to talk about what they do.

00:15:29.280 --> 00:15:31.670
And by the way journalists love to talk about
what we do.

00:15:31.670 --> 00:15:35.530
And we keep of course we keep secrets about
what stories we're working on, but we can

00:15:35.530 --> 00:15:39.670
talk ad nauseam about craft and past stories
and whatnot.

00:15:39.670 --> 00:15:44.620
And my understanding is that this is something
that Silicon Valley engineers enjoy engaging

00:15:44.620 --> 00:15:48.070
in; Apple people are told not to.

00:15:48.070 --> 00:15:53.600
And I describe in the book someone I know
who plays in a regular poker game with a group

00:15:53.600 --> 00:15:58.450
of Apple people and this person does not work
at Apple and when the subject of Apple comes

00:15:58.450 --> 00:16:04.680
up at the poker table the subject is changed.

00:16:04.680 --> 00:16:12.800
And so I've described Apple not only metaphorically
as the ultimate need-to-know culture but literally

00:16:12.800 --> 00:16:14.990
as the ultimate need-to-know culture.

00:16:14.990 --> 00:16:20.780
And this manifests itself in interesting linguistic
ways and also in physical ways.

00:16:20.780 --> 00:16:23.180
So Apple is a culture of disclosure.

00:16:23.180 --> 00:16:29.010
I say to you, "Are you disclosed on the following?"
and I have to do a little kabuki if I don't

00:16:29.010 --> 00:16:32.380
know if you're disclosed on it, I can't exactly
say what it is.

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:36.850
But if everyone in a meeting isn't disclosed
then not everyone is welcome at the meeting.

00:16:36.850 --> 00:16:43.040
And this is true also in a physical sense
and I describe in the book how you'll be working

00:16:43.040 --> 00:16:47.780
and all of a sudden barriers go up, windows
that were clear become frosted, doors that

00:16:47.780 --> 00:16:56.080
didn't exist now exist, security badges that
once got you in to a certain area no longer

00:16:56.080 --> 00:16:57.570
get you into the area.

00:16:57.570 --> 00:17:01.640
And if you're a typical worker what you know
is that there's a new project underfoot and

00:17:01.640 --> 00:17:02.790
that's all you know.

00:17:02.790 --> 00:17:08.000
If you knew you're badge would get you into
that area and it doesn't.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:14.539
And most interestingly to me I've been told
again more than once, people telling me that

00:17:14.539 --> 00:17:20.220
their bosses did not have access to the same
areas that they had access to for reasons

00:17:20.220 --> 00:17:24.860
that they didn't necessarily understand.

