in Fortune Magazine in May of last year, it's

00:17:30.029 --> 00:17:33.659
actually highly accurate but you're not expected
to be able to read the fine print from where

00:17:33.659 --> 00:17:34.870
you're sitting.

00:17:34.870 --> 00:17:41.160
But the key is this, and I like to say that
candidly this was more dramatic when Steve

00:17:41.160 --> 00:17:45.480
Jobs, the Sun King, was at the center and
the planets were revolving around him.

00:17:45.480 --> 00:17:50.230
This is in fact how Apple operates but I think
one of the great unknowns is how it will continue

00:17:50.230 --> 00:17:55.549
to operate with Cook as the CEO or whoever
follows him.

00:17:55.549 --> 00:18:01.240
But what you can see from this is what you
might expect from Apple an incredibly tight

00:18:01.240 --> 00:18:07.390
and an incredibly focused org chart where
the CEO, this ring around the inner circle

00:18:07.390 --> 00:18:11.870
are the vice presidents of Apple and I've
got most but not all of them there.

00:18:11.870 --> 00:18:18.140
It's a very small number of vice presidents
and the CEO can reach down no more than one

00:18:18.140 --> 00:18:24.009
layer to really touch just about everything
that's going on at the company.

00:18:24.009 --> 00:18:27.980
As part of the culture, by the way, you won't
be surprised to learn that org charts are

00:18:27.980 --> 00:18:32.570
frowned up at Apple; Apple doesn't create
and print org charts.

00:18:32.570 --> 00:18:37.669
And I was told that people were visibly nervous
having my org chart from Fortune Magazine

00:18:37.669 --> 00:18:43.800
on their desks last year.

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:50.929
Apple's famous for sweating the details and
the example I give in the book is the packaging

00:18:50.929 --> 00:18:59.019
design room where a package designer had hundreds
of prototypes of iPod boxes and their sole

00:18:59.019 --> 00:19:05.529
mission, and Apple teaches this, this case
by the way is an example of attention to detail.

00:19:05.529 --> 00:19:09.610
This person's sole mission was to peel off
that little piece of clear tape that seals

00:19:09.610 --> 00:19:15.240
your box and do this over and over and make
sure that the placement was just perfect.

00:19:15.240 --> 00:19:21.950
Now it sounds silly except, and I won't ask
for a show of hands because it could be incriminating,

00:19:21.950 --> 00:19:27.409
but is there anyone in the room who has experienced
the joy of peeling off that piece of tape

00:19:27.409 --> 00:19:33.000
and opening their iPod or iPhone box and taking
the product out and seeing how everything

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:37.750
is laid perfectly and then taking their device
out and feeling this sense of joy?

00:19:37.750 --> 00:19:38.750
[laughter]

00:19:38.750 --> 00:19:42.419
Okay, I do have smiles and chuckles in the
room, maybe some nervous laughter.

00:19:42.419 --> 00:19:49.039
But this is just one example and this pervades
the organization and so you get a sense of

00:19:49.039 --> 00:19:54.190
why details are important at Apple.

00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:58.380
Jobs was famous for saying that he didn't
think that Apple should do customer research

00:19:58.380 --> 00:20:04.820
and instead how could customers possibly know
what they wanted when they don't know what

00:20:04.820 --> 00:20:08.250
the product is that we're going to give them,
and we'll give them the products that we think

00:20:08.250 --> 00:20:09.380
they should have.

00:20:09.380 --> 00:20:15.200
By the way, Jobs especially later in life
like many of us was famous for repeating the

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:19.620
same lines over and over again and this was
one of his favorites because it resonated

00:20:19.620 --> 00:20:25.070
so well because it's exactly the opposite
of how other people, how other companies do

00:20:25.070 --> 00:20:26.820
things.

00:20:26.820 --> 00:20:32.669
We now know that integration is key to the
Apple's excellence and the integration that

00:20:32.669 --> 00:20:37.410
this typically refers to, and it's something
that Jobs spoke about, was the integration

00:20:37.410 --> 00:20:39.210
of hardware and software.

00:20:39.210 --> 00:20:45.600
And it's sort of astounding that over the
past 15 years really only Apple has been particularly

00:20:45.600 --> 00:20:50.580
excellent at integrating its own hardware
and software and its competitors have been

00:20:50.580 --> 00:20:53.009
bifurcated in hardware and software.

00:20:53.009 --> 00:20:59.169
But my point is that the whole company is
integrated extremely well, Apple is not whimsical

00:20:59.169 --> 00:21:05.230
as its advertising might suggest but extremely
planned, extremely well organized, things

00:21:05.230 --> 00:21:10.990
happen according to a timeline that is written
down, and the various parts of the company

00:21:10.990 --> 00:21:16.900
work well together in the past by force of
will because Jobs made sure that people worked

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:18.480
well together.

00:21:18.480 --> 00:21:22.460
But a key to understanding Apple is the importance
of design.

00:21:22.460 --> 00:21:27.240
And again Jony Ive has become famous as the
head of industrial design at Apple, but what's

00:21:27.240 --> 00:21:32.470
less well understood is just how important
his seat at the table has been.

00:21:32.470 --> 00:21:37.960
And you can glean this from the fact that
at Apple it would be inconceivable for say

00:21:37.960 --> 00:21:45.500
a financial person to sit in on the same early
product development meeting where Jony Ive

00:21:45.500 --> 00:21:50.200
or Jony Ive's people would have a conversation
about what the product would look like.

00:21:50.200 --> 00:21:55.410
Steve Jobs, at least initially, would have
been completely uninterested in a finance

00:21:55.410 --> 00:22:02.330
person's opinion of what it might cost to
do that or how we might pay for it or what

00:22:02.330 --> 00:22:07.190
kind of revenue we might be able to get from
it; this is antithetical to the Apple way

00:22:07.190 --> 00:22:08.289
of thinking.

00:22:08.289 --> 00:22:15.309
I likened it to a corollary to the personal
maxim of, "Do what you love and the money

00:22:15.309 --> 00:22:16.379
will follow."

00:22:16.379 --> 00:22:22.650
It's a little corny, I have to refine that
but it really does I think express Jobs' approach

00:22:22.650 --> 00:22:26.970
to product was, "First we'll think of the
product, then we'll think of how to make it

00:22:26.970 --> 00:22:33.529
beautiful and how to make it really good,
then we'll figure out what the market is for

00:22:33.529 --> 00:22:34.529
it."

00:22:34.529 --> 00:22:39.570
And I would submit to you that's not the normal
decision making process at your typical big

00:22:39.570 --> 00:22:42.179
company.

00:22:42.179 --> 00:22:49.149
A hallmark of Apple's entire way of doing
business is the power of saying no, and this

00:22:49.149 --> 00:22:52.919
is across the business and across product
development.

00:22:52.919 --> 00:22:58.090
It says no to industries to get involved in,
to who it will sell to, we know that it's

00:22:58.090 --> 00:23:03.249
been famously uninterested in selling to big
businesses over the years, which by the way

00:23:03.249 --> 00:23:04.450
has some history.

00:23:04.450 --> 00:23:08.960
Apple got beaten up badly in the 80's selling
to the enterprise and this scarred Jobs, many

00:23:08.960 --> 00:23:14.169
things scarred Jobs including this almost
running out of cash at the beginning.

00:23:14.169 --> 00:23:17.580
I have to tell you that I showed this slide
at Microsoft last week and I --

00:23:17.580 --> 00:23:18.960
[laughter]

00:23:18.960 --> 00:23:23.820
prepared them and I said, "Please don't take
this the wrong way," but I think it's very

00:23:23.820 --> 00:23:24.820
telling.

00:23:24.820 --> 00:23:29.110
What you get when you open your box of a PC
that you got at a retailer and what you get

00:23:29.110 --> 00:23:31.620
when you open your iMac box.

00:23:31.620 --> 00:23:36.399
I wanna do another slide that focuses more
on the screen because I think it's in the

00:23:36.399 --> 00:23:42.090
book and it's a very important part of Apple's
mentality of saying, "No."

00:23:42.090 --> 00:23:47.320
You know what the screen on an iMac looks
like when you turn it on, I need to show what

00:23:47.320 --> 00:23:52.559
the screen of a PC looks like especially if
you buy it from a retailer, your screen is

00:23:52.559 --> 00:23:56.619
littered with what Jobs referred as, "Crapware."

00:23:56.619 --> 00:24:01.950
And Crapware are these icons from various
vendors that the retailers or the manufacturers

00:24:01.950 --> 00:24:05.759
have done a deal with to goose their margin
a little bit.

00:24:05.759 --> 00:24:10.970
I would suggest that it's nothing short of
insulting to the customer to put that on the

00:24:10.970 --> 00:24:14.480
screen and it's something Apple wouldn't dream
of doing.

00:24:14.480 --> 00:24:18.510
Apple has faults by the way, but this is something
Apple's very good at.

00:24:18.510 --> 00:24:24.830
I could go on about the beauty of saying no;
Jobs would say that saying no is more important

00:24:24.830 --> 00:24:26.309
than saying yes.

00:24:26.309 --> 00:24:32.350
This extends to how Apple cooperates or engages
with the rest of the world.

00:24:32.350 --> 00:24:36.789
Most companies will send its people out to
events to interact in the hope that there

00:24:36.789 --> 00:24:40.610
might be some intangible benefit from interacting.

00:24:40.610 --> 00:24:45.889
Apple even killed the trade show that it was
integral to starting although it was its own,

00:24:45.889 --> 00:24:46.889
Macworld.

00:24:46.889 --> 00:24:51.629
And then I just like showing this fanciful
slide of an Apple executive being in a chair

00:24:51.629 --> 00:24:55.929
at the World Economic Forum in Davos where
I was a few weeks ago.

00:24:55.929 --> 00:25:00.919
It's inconceivable to think of an Apple person
engaging in jawboning and talking about making

00:25:00.919 --> 00:25:03.360
the world a better place in Davos.

00:25:03.360 --> 00:25:04.360
[laughter]

00:25:04.360 --> 00:25:09.519
With what's going on I shouldn't say inconceivable,
but it's until now impossible and I think

00:25:09.519 --> 00:25:12.240
highly unlikely in the near future.

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:16.889
You will know by the way if you see the CEO
of Apple on stage in Davos that things have

00:25:16.889 --> 00:25:20.570
really changed at Apple.

00:25:20.570 --> 00:25:24.159
Apple has this concept of the directly responsible
individual.

00:25:24.159 --> 00:25:27.970
It’s one of these things when I first heard
about it, first of all Apple people have been

00:25:27.970 --> 00:25:34.070
talking about for years this pre-dates Jobs'
return in 1997, it's not completely clear

00:25:34.070 --> 00:25:40.009
to me that it was even language that Jobs
was all that familiar with which magnifies

00:25:40.009 --> 00:25:43.190
its importance to me that it's so important
at Apple.

00:25:43.190 --> 00:25:48.240
At Apple there will be a list of items on
the agenda for a meeting, for example, and

00:25:48.240 --> 00:25:54.740
next to the action item will be a name, that
name is the DRI; the DRI is the one person

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:59.400
whose job it is to get the job done on that
specific task.

00:25:59.400 --> 00:26:04.630
It's so simple, it's so obvious, and yet my
hunch and I'm gonna try to test this with

00:26:04.630 --> 00:26:08.419
business school professors, is that most businesses
don't do it.

00:26:08.419 --> 00:26:11.190
And I know that I, oops, I don't know what
that's about.

00:26:11.190 --> 00:26:15.950
My Outlook is open, I apologize.

00:26:15.950 --> 00:26:20.039
I know there was a period when I was working
on the article at Fortune that I started to

00:26:20.039 --> 00:26:24.860
become obnoxious within my own company by
asking, "Well who's the DRI on that?"

00:26:24.860 --> 00:26:28.429
This was often on the telephone because most
of my colleagues are in New York, but I could

00:26:28.429 --> 00:26:33.950
feel the eyes rolling when I said it.

00:26:33.950 --> 00:26:38.730
I think it's unique that Apple is a massively
functional organization; this is the corollary

00:26:38.730 --> 00:26:45.090
to Jobs' aversion to general management; he
did not want jacks of all trades running businesses

00:26:45.090 --> 00:26:47.570
within the business, he wanted experts.

00:26:47.570 --> 00:26:51.770
He would brag that Apple employs the best
metallurgists in the world.

00:26:51.770 --> 00:26:59.210
And this is the case throughout the organization.

00:26:59.210 --> 00:27:03.610
This is I think one of the most important
and most controversial aspects of how Apple

00:27:03.610 --> 00:27:10.059
does business in that in selected instances
it behaves like a start-up.

00:27:10.059 --> 00:27:14.690
Of course Apples is not a start-up, I'm not
so naive as to think that it is; there are

00:27:14.690 --> 00:27:19.460
many elements of the company that behave just
like any big business anywhere.

00:27:19.460 --> 00:27:26.539
But where it's relevant, where Apple decides
that it's going to create something new and

00:27:26.539 --> 00:27:33.700
do something fresh, it manages to hive off
an area and let a relatively small group of

00:27:33.700 --> 00:27:38.190
people behave as if they are at a start-up.

00:27:38.190 --> 00:27:43.490
And I've likened this to a bunch of rich kids
in that they're off in a corner doing their

00:27:43.490 --> 00:27:49.539
own thing, but they have a very wealthy parent
funding their research, and in Apple's case

00:27:49.539 --> 00:27:56.269
this is a nearly $100 billion balance sheet
funding their research.

00:27:56.269 --> 00:28:01.470
I think by now since I wrote about it last
May it's become well known that Apple thinks

00:28:01.470 --> 00:28:04.940
a lot about the notion of small numbers.

00:28:04.940 --> 00:28:11.379
The British anthropologist Robin Dunbar referred
to the Dunbar's number as being about 150

00:28:11.379 --> 00:28:17.020
or smaller, that most humans really can't
relate to a group of people much bigger than

00:28:17.020 --> 00:28:18.720
about 150.

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:22.590
He was looking at primates in the wild, by
the way, but he decided that that was applicable

00:28:22.590 --> 00:28:24.440
to humans as well.

00:28:24.440 --> 00:28:29.919
And in fact for years Apple has been having
this ultra top secret retreat of about 100

00:28:29.919 --> 00:28:36.010
people whom Jobs characterized as the people
he would want to take with him if he were

00:28:36.010 --> 00:28:40.690
to leave Apple, the 100 or so most important
people.

00:28:40.690 --> 00:28:45.450
Very interestingly to me, by the way, this
was not a rank thing with Jobs it was not

00:28:45.450 --> 00:28:50.730
a status thing it was who he literally thought
were the most important people, not necessarily

00:28:50.730 --> 00:28:52.299
by title.

00:28:52.299 --> 00:28:57.960
The stories about the top 100 are legendary
and typical Apple; Jobs would require everybody

00:28:57.960 --> 00:29:02.840
attending the meeting to be bussed down to
the Santa Cruz or Monterey area in a bus from

00:29:02.840 --> 00:29:04.059
Cupertino.

00:29:04.059 --> 00:29:10.450
And I had this image of certain senior executives
who had attained great wealth being forced

00:29:10.450 --> 00:29:15.019
to get on a bus and drive for an hour and
a half or a couple of hours because the boss

00:29:15.019 --> 00:29:17.369
didn't want them driving their own car.

00:29:17.369 --> 00:29:22.980
He would sweep the room for bugs beforehand,
legitimately paranoid that the competition

00:29:22.980 --> 00:29:27.470
might try to find out the secrets that were
going to be revealed at a top 100 meeting.

00:29:27.470 --> 00:29:33.489
And indeed products for the next 18 months
or so have been revealed at top 100 meetings.

00:29:33.489 --> 00:29:39.179
Given how secretive Apple is Jobs thought
that it was important for a slightly larger

00:29:39.179 --> 00:29:45.700
group than the 10 or so person executive team
to be exposed to what was coming down the

00:29:45.700 --> 00:29:46.700
pike.

00:29:46.700 --> 00:29:51.170
The rest of the company was not invited to
the meeting and would not be exposed.

00:29:51.170 --> 00:29:57.480
One of the fascinating elements of this secrecy
that I've learned, the sales people at Apple

00:29:57.480 --> 00:30:03.350
are particularly frustrated because they don't
find out about what's going on at the company

00:30:03.350 --> 00:30:06.960
in terms of new products any sooner than the
rest of us do.

00:30:06.960 --> 00:30:11.610
And if you think about again how different
that is from any normal company which obviously

00:30:11.610 --> 00:30:17.489
wants to prep the sales force so they can
sell the product that's coming.

00:30:17.489 --> 00:30:23.289
On the subject of exclusion, I'm also told
that Apple people to this day will gather

00:30:23.289 --> 00:30:29.890
in a cafeteria to watch a closed circuit television
broadcast of the major keynotes whether it's

00:30:29.890 --> 00:30:36.429
at Moscone or on their own campus because,
and I think this is so interesting, they’re

00:30:36.429 --> 00:30:40.409
learning about the product that's being revealed
for the very first time at the same time the

00:30:40.409 --> 00:30:43.169
public is, at the same time journalists are.

00:30:43.169 --> 00:30:48.070
This includes people who worked on the product
because they typically will only have seen

00:30:48.070 --> 00:30:55.690
the feature or the part of the feature that
they worked on.

00:30:55.690 --> 00:31:02.519
Apple's marketing I think it's fair to say
is brilliant; one of the premises of the marketing

00:31:02.519 --> 00:31:05.029
at Apple is staying on the script.

00:31:05.029 --> 00:31:09.200
I hope I'm not gushing too much and suggesting
that “1,000 songs in your pocket” is one

00:31:09.200 --> 00:31:14.580
of the more brilliant marketing lines in the
history of consumer electronics marketing.

00:31:14.580 --> 00:31:22.159
Obviously MP3 players existed before the existing,
the incumbent's stressed storage capacity

00:31:22.159 --> 00:31:27.710
of their devices, Apple did talk about storage
capacity in terms of pricing, but “1,000

00:31:27.710 --> 00:31:32.549
songs in your pocket”, who can't understand
that and who can't repeat it over and over?

00:31:32.549 --> 00:31:37.259
And that's another important that you'd think
would be normal in business but I think Apple

00:31:37.259 --> 00:31:38.840
does it better than most.

00:31:38.840 --> 00:31:45.109
I've described how first of all very few people
at Apple are allowed to speak publicly; it's

00:31:45.109 --> 00:31:51.919
a discreet, finite number that is defined
in preparation for a product launch and the

00:31:51.919 --> 00:31:57.570
language that they will use is preapproved
and agreed upon.

00:31:57.570 --> 00:32:02.710
And so I quote an executive who was approved
on the iPhone who explained to me in giving

00:32:02.710 --> 00:32:09.289
speeches on my book I can understand the mentality
that when you give this message over and over

00:32:09.289 --> 00:32:14.309
the intellectual or human tendency is to change
up your delivery because that's how you keep

00:32:14.309 --> 00:32:16.220
yourself entertained.

00:32:16.220 --> 00:32:23.139
But he said, "No when you're pitching an Apple
product you deliver it over and over exactly

00:32:23.139 --> 00:32:25.059
the way we agreed it was gonna be delivered.

00:32:25.059 --> 00:32:26.059
Why?

00:32:26.059 --> 00:32:30.039
Well because the listener's hearing it for
the first time and what we want is for the

00:32:30.039 --> 00:32:35.100
listener to repeat it to their friends and
for their friends to start repeating it and

00:32:35.100 --> 00:32:41.019
pretty soon it's being repeated back in the
marketplace exactly the way we wrote it."

00:32:41.019 --> 00:32:46.379
And it's a very pure and very understandable
approach when you think about it that way,

00:32:46.379 --> 00:32:50.659
but requires a ton of discipline.

00:32:50.659 --> 00:32:57.049
Sometimes I've described Apple as a company
of paradoxes because on the one hand Apple

00:32:57.049 --> 00:33:01.960
is described to me, Apple people describe
Apple as being resource constrained.

00:33:01.960 --> 00:33:06.100
I came to understand what they're really referring
to is people; it's very difficult to get enough

00:33:06.100 --> 00:33:08.549
of the right people on a project.

00:33:08.549 --> 00:33:13.200
But when Apple decides to make a product or
market a product they will spend whatever

00:33:13.200 --> 00:33:17.399
it takes for seemingly trivial expenditures.

00:33:17.399 --> 00:33:25.700
And so the story I tell in the book is of
Jobs' desire to illustrate iMovie HD in 2005,

00:33:25.700 --> 00:33:29.200
the first launch of the high def version of
iMovie.

00:33:29.200 --> 00:33:36.260
And there weren't a lot of HD cameras or HD
televisions in the marketplace at the time

00:33:36.260 --> 00:33:42.330
so he decided they should do a wedding because
he knew that people used iMovie to shoot weddings.

00:33:42.330 --> 00:33:46.720
So they shot a wedding, it was an Apple employee;
it was a beautiful, elegant affair at the

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:49.149
Officers Club at the Presidio in San Francisco.

00:33:49.149 --> 00:33:54.480
Only when Jobs decided his opinion was it
was too elegant, it was too stuffy and he

00:33:54.480 --> 00:33:59.990
said, "I want a beach, I want feet in the
sand, I want a tropical setting, Hawaii would

00:33:59.990 --> 00:34:00.990
be good."

00:34:00.990 --> 00:34:03.919
He was fond of Hawaii.

00:34:03.919 --> 00:34:07.129
This was three weeks before Macworld.

00:34:07.129 --> 00:34:11.030
And to make a long story short, finding a
beautiful actress who was getting married

00:34:11.030 --> 00:34:17.061
on Maui right before New Years', the team
got its image at tremendous expense and the

00:34:17.061 --> 00:34:22.830
expense was really irrelevant; this was for
a 30 second or so clip at Macworld; they were

00:34:22.830 --> 00:34:33.340
able to show iMovie HD in beautiful, emotional
terms; the money wasn't what mattered.

00:34:33.340 --> 00:34:40.220
So just to drive home the point, this is a
replica of an actual wall in a marketing building

00:34:40.220 --> 00:34:45.030
at Apple; if you're in this marketing group
after you go in the door in the morning you

00:34:45.030 --> 00:34:51.419
walk around this wall every single day on
your way to work to remind you what your approach

00:34:51.419 --> 00:34:54.220
to marketing should be at Apple.

00:34:54.220 --> 00:34:58.980
Only this isn't exactly how the wall appears,
this is.

00:34:58.980 --> 00:35:04.470
Apple has an interesting relationship with
the press and that includes me and I think

00:35:04.470 --> 00:35:09.400
there's a profound business point here; there's
only one subject generally that Apple views

00:35:09.400 --> 00:35:14.090
worthy of it discussing publicly and that's
its products; doesn't wanna talk about how

00:35:14.090 --> 00:35:18.740
it does business which is the subject of my
book, it doesn't wanna by and large with the

