00:51:13.400 --> 00:51:16.840
and ask people, "Are Apple employees happy?"

00:51:16.840 --> 00:51:23.910
And the standard response would be, "Apple
people tend to buy into the mission of the

00:51:23.910 --> 00:51:24.910
company."

00:51:24.910 --> 00:51:26.230
And I'd say, "Yes, but are they happy?"

00:51:26.230 --> 00:51:27.230
[laughter]

00:51:27.230 --> 00:51:31.720
And the response would be, "People take great
pride at Apple" [laughs]

00:51:31.720 --> 00:51:32.720
[laughter]

00:51:32.720 --> 00:51:36.200
in seeing their products used all over the
place," and so on.

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:46.391
And so I think it's not trivial or an understatement
to say that it helps, everyone want to be

00:51:46.391 --> 00:51:51.860
on a winning team and you're willing to overlook
quite a bit to be on that winning team.

00:51:51.860 --> 00:51:58.160
And I am not, I don't wanna suggest that Apple
is a joyless place because some people have

00:51:58.160 --> 00:52:05.000
drawn that conclusion from some of the stuff
in my book about Apple as a workplace, but

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:12.020
I think it's fair to say that joy and fun
is not at the top of the list.

00:52:12.020 --> 00:52:16.780
And I think again now trying to be non-judgmental
about this there's a certain purity about

00:52:16.780 --> 00:52:23.490
this from a shareholder perspective or from
a customer perspective, would I settle for

00:52:23.490 --> 00:52:29.270
a little bit less in ease of use, for example,
in exchange for a little more joy from the

00:52:29.270 --> 00:52:30.270
workforce?

00:52:30.270 --> 00:52:31.270
[laughter]

00:52:31.270 --> 00:52:32.270
I don't know.

00:52:32.270 --> 00:52:34.710
Should I take one more Bernadette or am I
done?

00:52:34.710 --> 00:52:35.710
One more please.

00:52:35.710 --> 00:52:36.710
Yeah.

